{{Infobox artist | name = Charles M. Lefferts | image = ContinentalArmy LeffertsWatercolor.jpg | imagesize = 150px | caption = A 1909 [[watercolor]] painting, by Charles M. Lefferts, a noted American artist, military historian, and member of the [[New York Historical Society]], depicting a variety of Continental Army uniforms, from the [[American Revolutionary War]]. | birth_name = Charles MacKubin Lefferts | birth_date = {{Birth date|1873|4|19|mf=y}} | birth_place = [[New York City, New York]], [[United States|U.S.]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1923|3|17|1873|4|19|mf=y}} | death_place = [[Port Washington, New York]], [[United States|U.S.]] | nationality = | field = [[Illustration]] | movement = | works = }}
'''Charles MacKubin Lefferts''' (April 19, 1873 &ndash; March 17, 1923) was an [[United States|American]] [[illustrator]] and [[soldier]]. He served on and off in the [[New York (state)|New York]] [[National Guard (United States)|National Guard]] from 1893 onwards and enlisted in the federal army in 1917. He retired from the army in 1921, having attained the rank of Lieutenant. In his early years he lived in [[Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania]], where he met his future wife Anne Harrison.
Lefferts spent most of his time outside of the military studying [[uniforms]] of the [[American Revolution]]. A self-taught artist, he recorded his meticulous research efforts by making many illustrations of uniforms used by all of the forces involved in the war and also by collection illustrations made by other artists. He was made a member of the [[New York Historical Society]] in 1909. Three years after his death, the society published many of his images and their descriptions in a book titled ''Uniforms of the Armies in the War of the American Revolution, 1775-1783''.
